</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Primary peritoneal tumors are uncommon lesions that arise from the mesothelial or submesothelial layers of the peritoneum. Primary malignant mesothelioma, multicystic mesothelioma, primary peritoneal serous carcinoma, leiomyomatosis peritonealis disseminata, and desmoplastic small round cell tumor are the most prominent of these rare lesions. Primary malignant mesothelioma is a highly aggressive malignancy that occurs most commonly in older men and that has a strong association with high levels of asbestos exposure. It manifests most often as diffuse sheetlike or nodular thickening of the peritoneal surfaces, but it may occasionally be a localized mass. Multicystic mesothelioma occurs most frequently in women and has benign or indolent biologic behavior in the majority of patients. It is a multilocular cystic mass that arises from the pelvic peritoneal surfaces. Primary peritoneal serous carcinoma occurs almost exclusively in women. It is histologically identical to ovarian serous carcinoma and may be indistinguishable from metastatic ovarian carcinoma at imaging studies. Leiomyomatosis peritonealis disseminata is a rare, benign proliferative process that also occurs exclusively in women and is characterized by multiple smooth muscle nodules throughout the peritoneum. Desmoplastic small round cell tumor is a highly aggressive malignancy of unknown origin that occurs most often in the peritoneal cavity of young men. This unusual group of tumors is linked together by a common site of origin and imaging manifestations that mimic those of peritoneal carcinomatosis. Knowledge of the spectrum of imaging findings in this group of primary peritoneal tumors, along with their clinical and pathologic characteristics, is important in the evaluation of patients with diffuse peritoneal disease.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.282075175">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.282075175">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c01a.jpeg" height="1218" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F1A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1a.</b>  Normal peritoneal anatomy and recesses in the upper abdomen. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal drawing of the right upper abdomen shows the right subphrenic space, bare area of the liver (arrow), and right subhepatic space. <b>(b)</b> Axial drawing of the upper abdomen at a level inferior to the bare area of the liver shows the right and left subphrenic spaces separated by the falciform ligament (arrow). The right subhepatic space (arrowhead) and the superior recess of the lesser sac (*) are shown.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F1A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c01b.jpeg" height="984" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F1B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1b.</b>  Normal peritoneal anatomy and recesses in the upper abdomen. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal drawing of the right upper abdomen shows the right subphrenic space, bare area of the liver (arrow), and right subhepatic space. <b>(b)</b> Axial drawing of the upper abdomen at a level inferior to the bare area of the liver shows the right and left subphrenic spaces separated by the falciform ligament (arrow). The right subhepatic space (arrowhead) and the superior recess of the lesser sac (*) are shown.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F1B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c02a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1140" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  Normal peritoneal reflections in the pelvis. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal drawing of the female pelvis shows the peritoneum lining the superior surfaces of the bladder, uterus, and anterior upper one-third of the rectum. The rectovaginal pouch is the space between the vagina and rectum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal drawing of the male pelvis shows the peritoneum lining the superior surface of the bladder and anterior rectum. The retrovesical space (arrow) is between the bladder and rectum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c02b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1213" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  Normal peritoneal reflections in the pelvis. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal drawing of the female pelvis shows the peritoneum lining the superior surfaces of the bladder, uterus, and anterior upper one-third of the rectum. The rectovaginal pouch is the space between the vagina and rectum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal drawing of the male pelvis shows the peritoneum lining the superior surface of the bladder and anterior rectum. The retrovesical space (arrow) is between the bladder and rectum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c03x.jpeg" height="909" width="1126" aria-labelledby="F3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3.</b>  Normal peritoneal histologic features. Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×100; hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain) shows a single layer of flattened mesothelial cells (arrows) with adipose tissue, scattered chronic inflammatory cells, and vessels in the submesothelial space.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c04a.jpeg" height="913" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  Gross pathologic features of a peritoneal malignant mesothelioma. <b>(a)</b> Intraoperative photograph of a diffuse peritoneal malignant mesothelioma in a 51-year-old man with a history of asbestos exposure shows innumerable tumor nodules (arrows) scattered over the omental surfaces. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the cut surface of a resected specimen of a localized peritoneal malignant mesothelioma from a 47-year-old man who had no history of asbestos exposure shows a solitary, macrolobulated mass with foci of intratumoral degeneration and hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c04b.jpeg" height="913" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  Gross pathologic features of a peritoneal malignant mesothelioma. <b>(a)</b> Intraoperative photograph of a diffuse peritoneal malignant mesothelioma in a 51-year-old man with a history of asbestos exposure shows innumerable tumor nodules (arrows) scattered over the omental surfaces. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the cut surface of a resected specimen of a localized peritoneal malignant mesothelioma from a 47-year-old man who had no history of asbestos exposure shows a solitary, macrolobulated mass with foci of intratumoral degeneration and hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c05a.jpeg" height="657" width="806" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Epithelial peritoneal malignant mesothelioma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) shows invasive neoplastic mesothelial cells that extend through the submesothelial layer of the peritoneum. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×200; H-E stain) shows a microglandular structure lined by neoplastic cells (arrow) that are cuboidal and contain prominent nuclei.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c05b.jpeg" height="710" width="870" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Epithelial peritoneal malignant mesothelioma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) shows invasive neoplastic mesothelial cells that extend through the submesothelial layer of the peritoneum. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×200; H-E stain) shows a microglandular structure lined by neoplastic cells (arrow) that are cuboidal and contain prominent nuclei.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c06a.jpeg" height="667" width="921" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  Sarcomatous peritoneal malignant mesothelioma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) shows closely packed spindle cells that infiltrate the peritoneum. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×200; H-E stain) shows polymorphic spindle cells.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c06b.jpeg" height="742" width="1024" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  Sarcomatous peritoneal malignant mesothelioma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) shows closely packed spindle cells that infiltrate the peritoneum. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×200; H-E stain) shows polymorphic spindle cells.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g07a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  Epithelial peritoneal malignant mesothelioma in a 70-year-old man who complained of weight loss, early satiety, and abdominal distention. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT scans obtained after intravenously injected <b>(a)</b> and orally administered <b>(b)</b> contrast material show ascites, sheetlike thickening of the peritoneum (arrows in <b>a</b>); peritoneal nodules (arrows in <b>b</b>); and a large, heterogeneously enhancing mass in the greater omentum (*). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected omental mass shows confluent white-yellow tumor nodules. Scale is in centimeters.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g07b.jpeg" height="1284" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  Epithelial peritoneal malignant mesothelioma in a 70-year-old man who complained of weight loss, early satiety, and abdominal distention. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT scans obtained after intravenously injected <b>(a)</b> and orally administered <b>(b)</b> contrast material show ascites, sheetlike thickening of the peritoneum (arrows in <b>a</b>); peritoneal nodules (arrows in <b>b</b>); and a large, heterogeneously enhancing mass in the greater omentum (*). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected omental mass shows confluent white-yellow tumor nodules. Scale is in centimeters.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F7B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c07c.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F7C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7c.</b>  Epithelial peritoneal malignant mesothelioma in a 70-year-old man who complained of weight loss, early satiety, and abdominal distention. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT scans obtained after intravenously injected <b>(a)</b> and orally administered <b>(b)</b> contrast material show ascites, sheetlike thickening of the peritoneum (arrows in <b>a</b>); peritoneal nodules (arrows in <b>b</b>); and a large, heterogeneously enhancing mass in the greater omentum (*). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected omental mass shows confluent white-yellow tumor nodules. Scale is in centimeters.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F7C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g08x.jpeg" height="1382" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8.</b>  Epithelial diffuse peritoneal malignant mesothelioma in a 63-year-old man who complained of abdominal pain. Intravenous contrast material–enhanced CT scan shows fine, nodular soft tissue within the greater omentum (arrows) and no ascites. There is a small pneumoperitoneum and gas in the anterior abdominal wall from a previous open biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g09a.jpeg" height="1230" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  Epithelial diffuse peritoneal malignant mesothelioma in a 55-year-old man who formerly worked in a shipyard and complained of abdominal discomfort. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scans show complex ascites, serosal implants on the liver margin (black arrows in <b>a</b>), extension of the tumor across the diaphragm (white arrow in <b>a</b>), and extensive tumor encasement of the small bowel (arrows in <b>b</b>). The tumor also extends throughout the small bowel mesentery. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the small bowel and mesentery at autopsy shows thick, nodular tumor on the serosal surface of the bowel and throughout the mesentery. The opened segment of the small bowel (arrow) shows tumor thickening the bowel wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g09b.jpeg" height="1243" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  Epithelial diffuse peritoneal malignant mesothelioma in a 55-year-old man who formerly worked in a shipyard and complained of abdominal discomfort. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scans show complex ascites, serosal implants on the liver margin (black arrows in <b>a</b>), extension of the tumor across the diaphragm (white arrow in <b>a</b>), and extensive tumor encasement of the small bowel (arrows in <b>b</b>). The tumor also extends throughout the small bowel mesentery. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the small bowel and mesentery at autopsy shows thick, nodular tumor on the serosal surface of the bowel and throughout the mesentery. The opened segment of the small bowel (arrow) shows tumor thickening the bowel wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c09c.jpeg" height="832" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F9C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9c.</b>  Epithelial diffuse peritoneal malignant mesothelioma in a 55-year-old man who formerly worked in a shipyard and complained of abdominal discomfort. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scans show complex ascites, serosal implants on the liver margin (black arrows in <b>a</b>), extension of the tumor across the diaphragm (white arrow in <b>a</b>), and extensive tumor encasement of the small bowel (arrows in <b>b</b>). The tumor also extends throughout the small bowel mesentery. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the small bowel and mesentery at autopsy shows thick, nodular tumor on the serosal surface of the bowel and throughout the mesentery. The opened segment of the small bowel (arrow) shows tumor thickening the bowel wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F9C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g10a.jpeg" height="1243" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10a.</b>  Epithelial diffuse peritoneal malignant mesothelioma in a 73-year-old man who had a long history of asbestos exposure and complained of weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan shows sheetlike thickening of the anterior peritoneum (arrows), encasement of the small bowel, and pleating of the small bowel mesentery (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Image from a barium examination shows separation of small bowel segments and irregular fold thickening of small bowel segments in the left lower abdomen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F10A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g10b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1269" aria-labelledby="F10B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10b.</b>  Epithelial diffuse peritoneal malignant mesothelioma in a 73-year-old man who had a long history of asbestos exposure and complained of weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan shows sheetlike thickening of the anterior peritoneum (arrows), encasement of the small bowel, and pleating of the small bowel mesentery (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Image from a barium examination shows separation of small bowel segments and irregular fold thickening of small bowel segments in the left lower abdomen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F10B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g11a.jpeg" height="1403" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Epithelial diffuse peritoneal malignant mesothelioma in a 68-year-old man with a history of asbestos exposure and who complained of increasing abdominal girth and early satiety. Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scans show calcified asbestos-related pleural plaques (arrows in <b>a</b>) and massive thickening of the peritoneum (* in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g11b.jpeg" height="1315" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Epithelial diffuse peritoneal malignant mesothelioma in a 68-year-old man with a history of asbestos exposure and who complained of increasing abdominal girth and early satiety. Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scans show calcified asbestos-related pleural plaques (arrows in <b>a</b>) and massive thickening of the peritoneum (* in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g12x.jpeg" height="1188" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12.</b>  Localized peritoneal malignant mesothelioma with mixed histologic features in a 47-year-old man who complained of left-sided pain and who had no history of asbestos exposure. Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a heterogeneously enhancing mass (*) arising in the region of the gastrosplenic ligament that is adherent to the splenic flexure of the colon. The mass invades the abdominal wall (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g13a.jpeg" height="1287" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13a.</b>  Sarcomatous diffuse malignant mesothelioma in a 47-year-old woman who complained of abdominal pain and distention. Axial MR images of the pelvis show ascites and nodular tumor masses that are isointense relative to muscle with T1 weighting (arrows in <b>a</b>) and slightly hyperintense relative to muscle with T2 weighting (arrows in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F13A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g13b.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13b.</b>  Sarcomatous diffuse malignant mesothelioma in a 47-year-old woman who complained of abdominal pain and distention. Axial MR images of the pelvis show ascites and nodular tumor masses that are isointense relative to muscle with T1 weighting (arrows in <b>a</b>) and slightly hyperintense relative to muscle with T2 weighting (arrows in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F13B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g14a.jpeg" height="1311" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14a.</b>  Diffuse malignant mesothelioma in a 74-year-old man with a history of asbestos exposure and who complained of diarrhea. <b>(a)</b> Longitudinal sonogram of the left lower quadrant shows ascites and peritoneal tumor nodules (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan shows the heterogeneously enhancing tumor in the greater omentum. There are areas of low-attenuation tumoral necrosis (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F14A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g14b.jpeg" height="1567" width="1710" aria-labelledby="F14B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14b.</b>  Diffuse malignant mesothelioma in a 74-year-old man with a history of asbestos exposure and who complained of diarrhea. <b>(a)</b> Longitudinal sonogram of the left lower quadrant shows ascites and peritoneal tumor nodules (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan shows the heterogeneously enhancing tumor in the greater omentum. There are areas of low-attenuation tumoral necrosis (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F14B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c15a.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F15A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15a.</b>  Gross pathologic features of multicystic mesothelioma. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of resected multicystic mesothelioma shows a grapelike cluster of thin-walled cysts of variable size. <b>(b)</b> Laparoscopic image of multicystic mesothelioma in a 31-year-old man shows innumerable translucent cysts studding the omental and peritoneal surface.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F15A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c15b.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F15B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15b.</b>  Gross pathologic features of multicystic mesothelioma. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of resected multicystic mesothelioma shows a grapelike cluster of thin-walled cysts of variable size. <b>(b)</b> Laparoscopic image of multicystic mesothelioma in a 31-year-old man shows innumerable translucent cysts studding the omental and peritoneal surface.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F15B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c16a.jpeg" height="746" width="973" aria-labelledby="F16A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16a.</b>  Multicystic mesothelioma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×100; H-E stain) shows multiple, thin-walled, irregularly shaped cysts (*) that contain eosinophilic fluid. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×100; H-E stain) shows loose fibrous stroma (*) between the cysts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F16A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c16b.jpeg" height="697" width="909" aria-labelledby="F16B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16b.</b>  Multicystic mesothelioma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×100; H-E stain) shows multiple, thin-walled, irregularly shaped cysts (*) that contain eosinophilic fluid. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×100; H-E stain) shows loose fibrous stroma (*) between the cysts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F16B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g17a.jpeg" height="1125" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F17A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17a.</b>  Multicystic mesothelioma in a 65-year-old woman with chronic pelvic pain. <b>(a)</b> Midline sagittal endovaginal sonogram of the pelvis shows a complex, multiseptated cystic mass (*) posterior to the uterus in the cul-de-sac. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal endovaginal sonogram of the right adnexal region demonstrates the complex cystic mass (arrow) adjacent to the right ovary.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F17A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g17b.jpeg" height="1125" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F17B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17b.</b>  Multicystic mesothelioma in a 65-year-old woman with chronic pelvic pain. <b>(a)</b> Midline sagittal endovaginal sonogram of the pelvis shows a complex, multiseptated cystic mass (*) posterior to the uterus in the cul-de-sac. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal endovaginal sonogram of the right adnexal region demonstrates the complex cystic mass (arrow) adjacent to the right ovary.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F17B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g18a.jpeg" height="1240" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18a.</b>  Multicystic mesothelioma in a 35-year-old man who complained of increasing abdominal girth. Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show a cystic mass with enhancing septa (arrow in <b>a</b>) that extend from the superior margin of the bladder (* in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F18A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g18b.jpeg" height="1240" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18b.</b>  Multicystic mesothelioma in a 35-year-old man who complained of increasing abdominal girth. Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show a cystic mass with enhancing septa (arrow in <b>a</b>) that extend from the superior margin of the bladder (* in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F18B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g19a.jpeg" height="1170" width="1638" aria-labelledby="F19A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19a.</b>  Multicystic mesothelioma in a 41-year-old man who complained of a 40-pound weight loss and whose condition was originally diagnosed as intractable ascites. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan of the abdomen shows a multiseptated, complex cystic mass located anterior to the small bowel. Thick septa within the cyst enhance (arrows) and mimic soft-tissue masses. <b>(b)</b> CT scan of the pelvis demonstrates that the cyst extends into the retrovesical pouch (*). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected specimen shows innumerable translucent, fluid-filled cysts in grapelike clusters. Scale is in centimeters.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F19A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g19b.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F19B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19b.</b>  Multicystic mesothelioma in a 41-year-old man who complained of a 40-pound weight loss and whose condition was originally diagnosed as intractable ascites. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan of the abdomen shows a multiseptated, complex cystic mass located anterior to the small bowel. Thick septa within the cyst enhance (arrows) and mimic soft-tissue masses. <b>(b)</b> CT scan of the pelvis demonstrates that the cyst extends into the retrovesical pouch (*). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected specimen shows innumerable translucent, fluid-filled cysts in grapelike clusters. Scale is in centimeters.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F19B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c19c.jpeg" height="913" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F19C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19c.</b>  Multicystic mesothelioma in a 41-year-old man who complained of a 40-pound weight loss and whose condition was originally diagnosed as intractable ascites. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan of the abdomen shows a multiseptated, complex cystic mass located anterior to the small bowel. Thick septa within the cyst enhance (arrows) and mimic soft-tissue masses. <b>(b)</b> CT scan of the pelvis demonstrates that the cyst extends into the retrovesical pouch (*). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected specimen shows innumerable translucent, fluid-filled cysts in grapelike clusters. Scale is in centimeters.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F19C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g20a.jpeg" height="1633" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F20A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20a.</b>  Multicystic mesothelioma in an asymptomatic 60-year-old woman with a palpable mass found at pelvic examination. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows a multiseptated cystic mass (arrows) along the peritoneal surfaces of the uterus and broad ligaments. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal gadolinium-enhanced MR image reveals enhancement of the septa (arrow) and extension of the mass into the cul-de-sac.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F20A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g20b.jpeg" height="1633" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F20B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20b.</b>  Multicystic mesothelioma in an asymptomatic 60-year-old woman with a palpable mass found at pelvic examination. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows a multiseptated cystic mass (arrows) along the peritoneal surfaces of the uterus and broad ligaments. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal gadolinium-enhanced MR image reveals enhancement of the septa (arrow) and extension of the mass into the cul-de-sac.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F20B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c21a.jpeg" height="896" width="1164" aria-labelledby="F21A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21a.</b>  Primary peritoneal serous carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×100; H-E stain) shows glandlike areas (arrow) that contain cribiform and papillary architecture. <b>(b)</b> Higher-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×400; H-E stain) demonstrates atypical cells with large nuclei and prominent nucleoli.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F21A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c21b.jpeg" height="985" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F21B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21b.</b>  Primary peritoneal serous carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×100; H-E stain) shows glandlike areas (arrow) that contain cribiform and papillary architecture. <b>(b)</b> Higher-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×400; H-E stain) demonstrates atypical cells with large nuclei and prominent nucleoli.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F21B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c22x.jpeg" height="840" width="1101" aria-labelledby="F22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22.</b>  Psammomatous primary peritoneal serous carcinoma. Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) shows invasive tumor cells within a fibrous stroma (arrows). Laminated calcifications, or psammoma bodies, are seen (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g23a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F23A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23a.</b>  Primary peritoneal serous carcinoma in a 38-year-old woman who complained of abdominal distention and constipation. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show a moderate amount of ascites, enhancing soft-tissue nodules in the greater omentum (arrowheads in <b>a</b>), and normal ovaries (arrow in <b>b</b>). The right ovary contains a follicular cyst.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F23A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g23b.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F23B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23b.</b>  Primary peritoneal serous carcinoma in a 38-year-old woman who complained of abdominal distention and constipation. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show a moderate amount of ascites, enhancing soft-tissue nodules in the greater omentum (arrowheads in <b>a</b>), and normal ovaries (arrow in <b>b</b>). The right ovary contains a follicular cyst.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F23B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g24a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F24A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24a.</b>  Psammomatous primary peritoneal serous carcinoma in a 50-year-old woman who complained of abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show calcified nodules and soft-tissue caking of the greater omentum (arrowheads). There is a small collection of loculated ascites in the left lower pelvis. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected greater omentum shows infiltrating tumor (arrows) throughout the omental fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F24A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g24b.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F24B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24b.</b>  Psammomatous primary peritoneal serous carcinoma in a 50-year-old woman who complained of abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show calcified nodules and soft-tissue caking of the greater omentum (arrowheads). There is a small collection of loculated ascites in the left lower pelvis. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected greater omentum shows infiltrating tumor (arrows) throughout the omental fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F24B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c24c.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F24C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24c.</b>  Psammomatous primary peritoneal serous carcinoma in a 50-year-old woman who complained of abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show calcified nodules and soft-tissue caking of the greater omentum (arrowheads). There is a small collection of loculated ascites in the left lower pelvis. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected greater omentum shows infiltrating tumor (arrows) throughout the omental fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F24C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c25a.jpeg" height="910" width="1178" aria-labelledby="F25A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25a.</b>  Leiomyomatosis peritonealis disseminata. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) shows multiple circumscribed nodules of smooth muscle (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×100; H-E stain) shows interlacing fascicles of benign smooth muscle cells.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F25A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c25b.jpeg" height="663" width="858" aria-labelledby="F25B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25b.</b>  Leiomyomatosis peritonealis disseminata. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) shows multiple circumscribed nodules of smooth muscle (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×100; H-E stain) shows interlacing fascicles of benign smooth muscle cells.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F25B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g26a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F26A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26a.</b>  Leiomyomatosis peritonealis disseminata in a 31-year-old woman who had a history of uterine fibroids and who complained of lower abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show multiple enhancing masses throughout the peritoneum (arrows). There are innumerable masses in the pelvis. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image of the pelvis shows that the uterus (arrow) and peritoneal masses (arrowheads) are isointense relative to skeletal muscle. <b>(d)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image of the pelvis illustrates heterogeneous enhancement of the uterus (arrow) and peritoneal masses (arrowheads). <b>(e)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows low-signal-intensity peritoneal masses (arrowheads) and multiple discrete fibroids within the uterus (arrow). A small amount of ascites is also present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F26A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g26b.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F26B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26b.</b>  Leiomyomatosis peritonealis disseminata in a 31-year-old woman who had a history of uterine fibroids and who complained of lower abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show multiple enhancing masses throughout the peritoneum (arrows). There are innumerable masses in the pelvis. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image of the pelvis shows that the uterus (arrow) and peritoneal masses (arrowheads) are isointense relative to skeletal muscle. <b>(d)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image of the pelvis illustrates heterogeneous enhancement of the uterus (arrow) and peritoneal masses (arrowheads). <b>(e)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows low-signal-intensity peritoneal masses (arrowheads) and multiple discrete fibroids within the uterus (arrow). A small amount of ascites is also present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F26B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g26c.jpeg" height="1503" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F26C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26c.</b>  Leiomyomatosis peritonealis disseminata in a 31-year-old woman who had a history of uterine fibroids and who complained of lower abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show multiple enhancing masses throughout the peritoneum (arrows). There are innumerable masses in the pelvis. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image of the pelvis shows that the uterus (arrow) and peritoneal masses (arrowheads) are isointense relative to skeletal muscle. <b>(d)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image of the pelvis illustrates heterogeneous enhancement of the uterus (arrow) and peritoneal masses (arrowheads). <b>(e)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows low-signal-intensity peritoneal masses (arrowheads) and multiple discrete fibroids within the uterus (arrow). A small amount of ascites is also present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F26C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g26d.jpeg" height="1503" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F26D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26d.</b>  Leiomyomatosis peritonealis disseminata in a 31-year-old woman who had a history of uterine fibroids and who complained of lower abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show multiple enhancing masses throughout the peritoneum (arrows). There are innumerable masses in the pelvis. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image of the pelvis shows that the uterus (arrow) and peritoneal masses (arrowheads) are isointense relative to skeletal muscle. <b>(d)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image of the pelvis illustrates heterogeneous enhancement of the uterus (arrow) and peritoneal masses (arrowheads). <b>(e)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows low-signal-intensity peritoneal masses (arrowheads) and multiple discrete fibroids within the uterus (arrow). A small amount of ascites is also present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F26D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g26e.jpeg" height="1556" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F26E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26e.</b>  Leiomyomatosis peritonealis disseminata in a 31-year-old woman who had a history of uterine fibroids and who complained of lower abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show multiple enhancing masses throughout the peritoneum (arrows). There are innumerable masses in the pelvis. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image of the pelvis shows that the uterus (arrow) and peritoneal masses (arrowheads) are isointense relative to skeletal muscle. <b>(d)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image of the pelvis illustrates heterogeneous enhancement of the uterus (arrow) and peritoneal masses (arrowheads). <b>(e)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows low-signal-intensity peritoneal masses (arrowheads) and multiple discrete fibroids within the uterus (arrow). A small amount of ascites is also present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F26E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c27a.jpeg" height="638" width="832" aria-labelledby="F27A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27a.</b>  Desmoplastic small round cell tumor. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) depicts cords of undifferentiated, uniform, small, round cells surrounded by a dense collagenous stroma (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Higher-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×400; H-E stain) shows the tumor cells with scant cytoplasm and large, hyperchromatic nuclei (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F27A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c27b.jpeg" height="834" width="1088" aria-labelledby="F27B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27b.</b>  Desmoplastic small round cell tumor. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) depicts cords of undifferentiated, uniform, small, round cells surrounded by a dense collagenous stroma (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Higher-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×400; H-E stain) shows the tumor cells with scant cytoplasm and large, hyperchromatic nuclei (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F27B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F28A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g28a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F28A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 28a.</b>  Desmoplastic small round cell tumor in a 42-year-old man who complained of right upper quadrant pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show multiple liver metastases (arrows in <b>a</b>) and a large, circumscribed pelvic mass (arrows in <b>b</b>). The pelvic mass contains central hypoattenuation, indicative of tumor necrosis. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected pelvic mass shows its well-defined borders and central tumor necrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F28A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F28B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g28b.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F28B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 28b.</b>  Desmoplastic small round cell tumor in a 42-year-old man who complained of right upper quadrant pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show multiple liver metastases (arrows in <b>a</b>) and a large, circumscribed pelvic mass (arrows in <b>b</b>). The pelvic mass contains central hypoattenuation, indicative of tumor necrosis. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected pelvic mass shows its well-defined borders and central tumor necrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F28B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F28C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29c28c.jpeg" height="1021" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F28C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 28c.</b>  Desmoplastic small round cell tumor in a 42-year-old man who complained of right upper quadrant pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show multiple liver metastases (arrows in <b>a</b>) and a large, circumscribed pelvic mass (arrows in <b>b</b>). The pelvic mass contains central hypoattenuation, indicative of tumor necrosis. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected pelvic mass shows its well-defined borders and central tumor necrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F28C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F29A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g29a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F29A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 29a.</b>  Desmoplastic small round cell tumor in a previously asymptomatic 16-year-old boy who was imaged following a motor vehicle accident and found to have a splenic laceration, hemoperitoneum, and peritoneal masses. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show the hemoperitoneum and multiple solid intraperitoneal masses (arrows in <b>a</b>). Some of the masses contain calcifications (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F29A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F29B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g29b.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F29B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 29b.</b>  Desmoplastic small round cell tumor in a previously asymptomatic 16-year-old boy who was imaged following a motor vehicle accident and found to have a splenic laceration, hemoperitoneum, and peritoneal masses. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans of the abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pelvis <b>(b)</b> show the hemoperitoneum and multiple solid intraperitoneal masses (arrows in <b>a</b>). Some of the masses contain calcifications (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F29B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F30A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g30a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F30A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 30a.</b>  Desmoplastic small round cell tumor with bone metastasis in a 31-year-old man who complained of pelvic pressure and difficulty in urinating. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan of the pelvis shows a large heterogeneous mass (arrow) posterior to the bladder and anterior to the rectum. <b>(b)</b> Coronal T1-weighted MR image demonstrates that the pelvic mass is hypointense and reveals an infiltrative hypointense mass within the marrow space of the left proximal femur. <b>(c)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows that the pelvic mass has heterogeneous high signal intensity and that the left proximal femur metastasis has associated high signal marrow edema. <b>(d)</b> Coronal gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the primary pelvic tumor as well as of the femoral metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F30A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F30B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g30b.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F30B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 30b.</b>  Desmoplastic small round cell tumor with bone metastasis in a 31-year-old man who complained of pelvic pressure and difficulty in urinating. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan of the pelvis shows a large heterogeneous mass (arrow) posterior to the bladder and anterior to the rectum. <b>(b)</b> Coronal T1-weighted MR image demonstrates that the pelvic mass is hypointense and reveals an infiltrative hypointense mass within the marrow space of the left proximal femur. <b>(c)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows that the pelvic mass has heterogeneous high signal intensity and that the left proximal femur metastasis has associated high signal marrow edema. <b>(d)</b> Coronal gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the primary pelvic tumor as well as of the femoral metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F30B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F30C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g30c.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F30C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 30c.</b>  Desmoplastic small round cell tumor with bone metastasis in a 31-year-old man who complained of pelvic pressure and difficulty in urinating. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan of the pelvis shows a large heterogeneous mass (arrow) posterior to the bladder and anterior to the rectum. <b>(b)</b> Coronal T1-weighted MR image demonstrates that the pelvic mass is hypointense and reveals an infiltrative hypointense mass within the marrow space of the left proximal femur. <b>(c)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows that the pelvic mass has heterogeneous high signal intensity and that the left proximal femur metastasis has associated high signal marrow edema. <b>(d)</b> Coronal gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the primary pelvic tumor as well as of the femoral metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F30C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F30D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.282075175/asset/images/g08mr29g30d.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F30D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 30d.</b>  Desmoplastic small round cell tumor with bone metastasis in a 31-year-old man who complained of pelvic pressure and difficulty in urinating. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan of the pelvis shows a large heterogeneous mass (arrow) posterior to the bladder and anterior to the rectum. <b>(b)</b> Coronal T1-weighted MR image demonstrates that the pelvic mass is hypointense and reveals an infiltrative hypointense mass within the marrow space of the left proximal femur. <b>(c)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows that the pelvic mass has heterogeneous high signal intensity and that the left proximal femur metastasis has associated high signal marrow edema. <b>(d)</b> Coronal gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the primary pelvic tumor as well as of the femoral metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.282075175&amp;id=F30D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Churg</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">A</span></span>, Cagle PT, Roggli VL. Tumors of the serosal membranes. Silver Spring, Md: ARP, 2006.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=ChurgA%2C+Cagle+PT%2C+Roggli+VL.+Tumors+of+the+serosal+membranes.+Silver+Spring%2C+Md%3A+ARP%2C+2006.">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="R2" class="citations"><di